LAGOS – The Apapa Command of the Nigeria Customs Service (NCS), said it has netted a whopping sum of N264,536,201,293.71 as revenue into the federation account in the first quarter of 2022. The Command disclosed that the revenue figure showed a significant increase of N104 billion as against N159 billion collected in the corresponding first quarter of the year 2021. It added that this represented an increase of 65.7% in revenue collection which the command generated into the Federal government coffers. The Command also disclosed that in the area of anti-smuggling and through various rigorous efforts as well as shared intelligence, it intercepted 46 Containers of various items with a Duty Paid Value(DPV) of N1,142,876,606.00 as against 28 seizures made at the same quarter 2021. Comptroller Malanta Yusuf, Area Controller of Apapa Customs Command, disclosed this in Lagos, during a press briefing. He said some of the seizures include unregistered medicaments, such as tramadol and Codein syrup, unprocessed wood, used clothing, footwear, foreign parboiled rice and other sundry items that fall under the import/export prohibition list, that contravens the Customs and Excise Management Act (CEMA), CAP C45 of the law of the Federal Republic of Nigeria 2004. He disclosed that in line with the Federal government’s efforts to diversify the economy, goods amounting to the sum of N34,072,869,799.00 with a Free On Board (FOB) value of $87,992,356.10 (US) were exported through the command during the period as against the N30.2 billion which was equivalent to FOB value of $82.1 million (US) that the command handled between January and March 2021. CAC Yusuf appealed to all stakeholders to make sure that items on the import/export prohibition lists are observed and also to prepare themselves for the emerging realities of the Customs examination done through the non-intrusive inspection (NII) regime.